 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Murder?''\n| Barry Bostwick\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://mildlyfearsomefilms.com/murder-landing-page/cast.html|title=Barry Bostwick|website=Mildlyfearsomefilms.com|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\u20132016\n| ''Inside the Extras Studio''\n|  Milt Hamilton\n| 20 episodes\n|}\n\n==Stage productions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n\n|-\n| 1969\n| ''Cock-A-Doodle-Dandy''\n| Porter, The Cock\n| Broadway debut\n|-\n| 1969\n| ''[[Hamlet]]''\n| Ghost, Osric, Player\n| \n! Year 1970\n! Title House of Leather\n! Role(s) Donny Brook\n! Notes Closed after one night in NY.\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Soon (musical)|Soon]]''\n| Kelly\n| \n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]''\n| Danny Zuko\n| Nominated \u2013 [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical]]\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[They Knew What They Wanted (play)|They Knew What They Wanted]]''\n| Joe\n| Nominated \u2013 [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Play]]\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[The Robber Bridegroom (musical)|The Robber Bridegroom]]''\n| Jamie Lockhart\n| [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical]]\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]''\n| The Pirate King\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Nick & Nora]]''\n| Nick Charles\n| opposite [[Joanna Gleason]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Camelot (musical)|Camelot]]''\n| Merlyn\n|\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Association\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n| 1972\n| [[Tony Awards]]\n| [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Best Actor in a Musical]]\n| ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1976\n| [[Tony Awards]]\n| [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Play|Best Featured Actor in a Play]]\n| ''[[They Knew What They Wanted (play)|They Knew What They Wanted]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1977\n| [[Drama Desk Awards]]\n| [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actor in a Musical|Outstanding Actor in a Musical]]\n| ''[[The Robber Bridegroom (musical)|The Robber Bridegroom]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Awards]]\n| [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Best Actor in a Musical]]\n| ''The Robber Bridegroom''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 1978\n| [[New York Film Critics Circle Awards]]\n| [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| ''[[Movie Movie]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1979\n| [[National Society of Film Critics Awards]]\n| [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| ''Movie Movie''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1989\n| [[Golden Globe Awards]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]]\n| ''[[War and Remembrance (TV miniseries)|War and Remembrance]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2013\n| [[Fangoria Chainsaw Awards]]\n| [[Fangoria Chainsaw Awards|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| ''[[Some Guy Who Kills People]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Evans, David and Scott Michaels. ''Rocky Horror: Concept to Cult''. London: Sanctuary, 2002.\n* Lipton, Michael A. and Nancy Matsumoto. \u201cSerial Dad: Michael J. Fox Looks Up to 6\u20194\u201d Actor\u201d. People March 10, 1997: 99.\n* Uhry, Alfred. \"The Trail of the Robber B\". The Robber Bridegroom CD Liner Notes 1998: 2.\n* Hunt, Paula. \"Bostwick Tells Story of Survival\". Express-News, March 6, 2006.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|23289}}\n* {{IMDb name|960}}\n* {{amg name|7552}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Barry Bostwick\n|list =\n{{GoldenGlobeSupportingActorTV 1970-1989}}\n{{TonyAward MusicalLeadActor 1976-2000}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bostwick, Barry}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actor Golden Globe (television) winners]]\n[[Category:People from San Mateo, California]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:United States International University alumni]]\n[[Category:Tisch School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Audiobook narrators]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Barry Bostwick\n| image              = Barry Bostwick at GalaxyCon Louisville 2019.jpg\n| caption            = Bostwick at [[GalaxyCon]] Louisville in 2019\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1945|2|24}}<!--- 1945 is correct, according to California Birth Records --->\n| birth_place        = [[San Mateo, California|San Mateo]], California\n| birth_name         = Barry Knapp Bostwick\n| occupation         = Actor, singer\n| education          = [[Alliant International University|Alliant International University, San Diego]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[New York University]] {{small|([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])}}\n| years_active       = 1970\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Stacey Nelkin]]|1987|1991|reason=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|Sherri Jensen<br>|1994}}\n| children           = 2\n}}\n\n'''Barry Knapp Bostwick''' (born February 24, 1945<!--- 1945 is correct, according to California Birth Records --->) is an American stage and screen actor and singer. He is best known for portraying Brad Majors in the [[Musical film|musical]] [[comedy horror]] ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]'' (1975) and Mayor Randall Winston in the [[sitcom]] ''[[Spin City]]'' (1996\u20132002). He has also had considerable success in [[musical theatre]], winning a [[Tony Award]] for his role in ''[[The Robber Bridegroom (musical)|The Robber Bridegroom]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nBostwick was born in [[San Mateo, California]]. He is the son of Elizabeth \"Betty\" (n\u00e9e Defendorf), a housewife, and Henry \"Bud\" Bostwick, a city planner and actor.<ref>{{cite web | author= | title=Barry Bostwick Biography | work=filmreference | url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/41/Barry-Bostwick.html | year=2008 | accessdate=2008-06-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |title=Barry Bostwick Biography |work=Yahoo! Movies |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800021649/bio |year=2008 |accessdate=2008-06-07 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927210930/http://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800021649/bio |archivedate=2006-09-27 |df= }}</ref> His only sibling, Henry \"Pete\" Bostwick, was killed in a car accident on July 20, 1973.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/san-mateo-times/1973-07-20/|title=NewspaperArchive\u00ae - Newspaper Archives, Obituaries & Family History|website=Newspaperarchive.com|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> Bostwick attended San Diego's [[United States International University]] in 1967, majoring in acting, got his start on the Hillbarn Theatre stage now located in Foster City, and worked for a time as a circus performer. He also attended NYU's [[Tisch School of the Arts#Graduate Acting Program|Graduate Acting Program]], graduating in 1968.<ref>{{cite web | author= | title=NYU Graduate Acting Alumni | url=http://gradacting.tisch.nyu.edu/object/ga_alumbios.html | year=2011  | accessdate=2011-12-01}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1970, Bostwick was a member of a pop group called The Klowns, assembled and promoted by [[Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus]], whose members performed wearing stylized clown makeup and costumes. Their sole album, released in 1970, was produced by [[Jeff Barry]], and generated a minor ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' hit single, \"Lady Love\".\n\nBostwick replaced C.C. Courtney in the musical ''[[Salvation (musical)|Salvation]]''. His next stage appearance was in the 1971 rock opera ''[[Soon (musical)|Soon]]'', which closed after three performances. In 1972, Bostwick originated the role of bad boy [[Danny Zuko]] in the stage production of ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]'', earning a [[Tony Award]] nomination for his performance. This was followed by a voice role as Terr in the English-dubbed version of ''[[Fantastic Planet]]'' in 1973. He later starred with [[Tim Curry]] and [[Susan Sarandon]] in ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]'' (1975) portraying the character of Brad Majors. He also won a [[Tony Award]] for his performance in the 1977 musical ''[[The Robber Bridegroom (musical)|The Robber Bridegroom]]''. In 1981, Bostwick starred in the [[Foul Play (TV series)|TV series adaptation]] of the 1978 movie ''[[Foul Play (1978 film)|Foul Play]]'', with his role modeled after [[Chevy Chase]]'s and co-star [[Deborah Raffin]] in [[Goldie Hawn]]'s part. The following year, he starred in ''[[Megaforce]]''. Bostwick starred, along with [[Carl Weintraub]], as Rick Armstrong in the short-lived ABC sitcom ''[[Dads (1986 TV series)|Dads]]'' during the 1986-87 season.  From 1996 to 2002, Bostwick portrayed Randall Winston, the mayor of [[New York City]] in the [[situation comedy|sitcom]] ''[[Spin City]]'' opposite [[Michael J. Fox]] and his successor, [[Charlie Sheen]]. In 2006, Bostwick replaced [[Peter Scolari]] as Mr. Tyler, the father of [[Amanda Bynes]]' and [[Jennie Garth]]'s lead characters, on ''[[What I Like About You (TV series)|What I Like About You]]''.<ref name=\"imdb.com\">{{IMDb title|0759389|What I Like About You}}</ref>\n\nBostwick had a recurring role between 2004 and 2007 on ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''. He has also had leading roles in various mini-series, including ''[[George Washington (miniseries)|George Washington]]'', its sequel ''[[George Washington II: The Forging of a Nation]]'', ''[[Scruples (TV miniseries)|Scruples]]'', ''[[A Woman of Substance (miniseries)|A Woman of Substance]]'', ''[[War and Remembrance]]'', and ''[[Judith Krantz's Till We Meet Again|Till We Meet Again]]''.\n\nBostwick served as host of the nationally televised annual ''[[Fourth of July|Capitol Fourth]]'' celebration on the [[National Mall]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] for eight years. Bostwick was also seen in a [[Pepsi Twist]] commercial. In the ''[[Cold Case (TV series)|Cold Case]]'' episode \"Creatures of the Night\", in which he is the main suspect, the theme of the episode revolves around ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]'', which is among his best-known performances to date.\n\nIn 2003, Bostwick appeared on ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]'' as a patient diagnosed with [[prostate cancer]], a disease Bostwick had in real life. In 2008, he appeared in an episode of TV series ''[[Ugly Betty]]'' as an attorney to the Meade family. In 2007, Bostwick gained a recurring role, as Grandpa Clyde Flynn on the animated television series, ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]''. Bostwick is also the spokesperson for [[Optimum Voice]].<ref>{{cite web|author=  |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VdMJ5P8cSNI |title=Optimum Voice Commercial with Barry Bostwick |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2011-10-10}}</ref> In June 2009 he played Father Jimmy, the ineffective exorcist in the independent horror comedy ''The Selling'', written by Gabriel Diani and directed by Emily Lou.\n\nOther television credits include guest appearances in ''[[Charlie's Angels]]'', ''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]'', ''[[The Golden Palace]]'', ''[[Grace Under Fire (TV series)|Grace Under Fire]]'', and ''[[Las Vegas (TV series)|Las Vegas]]''.\n\nBostwick was supposed to appear on season 3 of ''[[Private Practice (TV series)|Private Practice]]'' as \"the Captain\", a father of the [[Addison Montgomery]] character, but had to resign due to a scheduling conflict.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fancast.com/blogs/matts-tv-news/private-practice-scoop-addisons-dad-is-sent-from-heaven/ |title='Private Practice' Scoop: Addison's Dad Is Sent from 'Heaven' &#124; XFINITY TV News |publisher=Fancast.com |date=2009-10-12 |accessdate=2011-10-10 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213120723/http://www.fancast.com/blogs/matts-tv-news/private-practice-scoop-addisons-dad-is-sent-from-heaven/ |archivedate=2009-12-13 |df= }}</ref> In 2011, Bostwick portrayed a small town sheriff in the [[John Landis]]-produced thriller ''[[Some Guy Who Kills People]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1568341/|title=Some Guy Who Kills People|publisher=IMDB}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BarryBostwickApr09.jpg|thumb|Bostwick at the premiere for ''[[Earth (2007 film)|Earth]]'' in April 2009]]\nIn October 2010, Bostwick briefly appeared in [[The Rocky Horror Glee Show|the ''Rocky Horror''-themed]] ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b199812_exclusive_rocky_horror_original.html|title=Exclusive: ''Rocky Horror'' Original Castmembers to Appear in ''Glee''{{'s}} Tribute Episode|first=Kristin|last=Dos Santos|authorlink=Kristin Dos Santos|date=September 10, 2010|publisher=[[E! Online|E!]]|accessdate=September 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSince 2009, Bostwick has had a recurring role as Roger Frank on the sitcom ''[[Cougar Town]]'' which stars [[Courteney Cox]]. In season 3 of the show we learn that Bostwick's character has become mayor of the town the comedy is set in, Gulf Haven. In 2015, he starred in [[Darren Lynn Bousman]]'s segment of the [[anthology film]] ''[[Tales of Halloween]]'', which was his second time acting under Bousman after ''[[The Devil's Carnival]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/86332/tales-halloween-interview-spotlight-barry-bostwick/|title=Tales of Halloween Interview Spotlight: Barry Bostwick - Dread Central|date=4 February 2015|website=Dreadcentral.com|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> and appeared in the [[comedy horror]] film ''Helen Keller vs. Nightwolves''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/94274/helen-keller-vs-nightwolves-sees-a-teaser-trailer/|title=Helen Keller vs. Nightwolves Sees a Teaser Trailer - Dread Central|date=24 March 2015|website=Dreadcentral.com|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> In 2015 he portrayed Collin Winthrop, father of the Gig Harbor Killer, in the season-ending ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]'' episode \"The End Game\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4145952/|title=The End Game|date=15 February 2015|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=8 October 2017|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> He has also had a return to cult musical horror films in the form of [[Terrance Zdunich]]'s ''[[Alleluia! The Devil's Carnival]]'', which is a sequel to the 2012 short film ''[[The Devil's Carnival]]'', which he was not previously a cast member of, being a newcomer to the franchise.\n\n==Personal life==\nBostwick married [[Stacey Nelkin]] in 1987, and they were divorced in 1991. He married his second wife Sherri Ellen Jensen in 1993; they have two children, a son and a daughter.<ref>Lipton, Michael L. [https://people.com/archive/serial-dad-vol-47-no-9/ \"Serial Dad\"] ''People'', March 10, 1997</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Bostwick was diagnosed with [[prostate cancer]], and had his prostate removed in July 1997.<ref>Moran Reed W. [http://www.usrf.org/news/Barry_Bostwick.html \"Barry Bostwick advises on prostate cancer\"] ''USA Today'', March 9, 2002</ref> In 2004, he won the [[Gilda Radner]] Courage Award from the [[Roswell Park Cancer Institute]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n==Select filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Jennifer on My Mind]]''\n| Minstrel #1\n|\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[Fantastic Planet]]''\n| Narrator\n| Voice role\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''Road Movie''\n| Hank\n|\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]''\n| Brad Majors\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Movie Movie]]''\n| Johnny Danko / Dick Cummings\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Megaforce]]''\n| Commander Ace Hunter\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''Parent Trap 3''\n| Jeffrey Wyatt\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''In the Heat of Passion II: Unfaithful''\n| Phillip\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Weekend at Bernie's II]]