{"title_page": "Seacombe railway station", "text_new": "{{Short description|Former railway station on the Wirral Railway in Wirral, England}}\n{{coord|53.4099|-3.0194|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=title}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n| name        = Seacombe\n| image       =[[File:Seacombe railway station 2042707 fbe01881.jpg|265px]]\n| caption     =The station in 1959\n| postgroup   = [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway|LMS]]\n| line        = [[Wirral Railway]]\n| locale      = [[Wallasey]]\n| borough     = [[Wirral Peninsula|Wirral]]\n| platforms   = 3\n| years       = 1 June 1895\n| events      = opened\n| years1      = 4 January 1960\n| events1     = passenger service withdrawn\n| years2      = 16 June 1963\n| events2     = closed completely\n| gridref     = SJ323908\n|}}\n<!-- start of article -->\n'''Seacombe railway station''' was located in [[Wallasey]], [[Wirral Peninsula|Wirral]], [[England]].<ref>[http://maps.nls.uk/geo/explore/#zoom=17&lat=53.4101&lon=-3.0197&layers=6&b=1 The station on a navigable Edwardian 6\" OS map with overlays, via ''National Library of Scotland'']</ref><ref>[http://www.RailMapOnline.com/UKIEMap.php?lat=53.40975&lng=-3.01865 The station on a navigable map with overlays, via ''Rail Map Online'']</ref> The station was opened by the [[Wirral Railway]] in 1895 and closed in 1963.\n\n==History==\nThe station was the terminus of a small branch line that ran from Seacombe Junction to opposite the ferry terminal at [[Seacombe]], adjacent to the [[River Mersey]].<ref name=MitchellXXXVI>{{harvnb|Mitchell|Smith|2013|loc=map XXXVI}}</ref> It was opened on 1 June 1895 as part of the [[Wirral Railway]], with only one other station ([[Liscard and Poulton railway station|Liscard and Poulton]]) on the stretch of line. The station's single platform was largely of timber construction with a small wooden waiting shelter near the exit. An additional platform was on the site,{{sfn|Aves|2011|p=330}} but was never used as the adjacent line was for the turning round of steam locomotives. The station buildings were constructed of [[corrugated iron]]. This was intended as a temporary measure, pending the building of a more permanent station adjoining the ferry terminal.<ref name=RSW>{{harvnb|Merseyside Railway History Group|1994|pages=50\u201351}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 1901 Seacombe became '''Seacombe & Egremont''', then reverted to its original name on 5 January 1953. The station saw regular passenger trips to [[Birkenhead]], [[New Brighton, Merseyside|New Brighton]] and [[Chester]] with occasional specials to [[Wrexham]] and [[West Kirby]]. However, the line was more focused on goods rather than passengers, so when the majority of the Wirral Railway was electrified in 1938 the Seacombe branch was omitted. Passenger services ended on 4 January 1960,<ref name=Mitchell108>{{harvnb|Mitchell|Smith|2013|loc=fig. 108}}</ref> although goods services continued for three further years until the station closed completely on 16 June 1963.<ref name=RSW /><ref name=DRS>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subbrit.org.uk/sb-sites/stations/s/seacombe/index.shtml|title=Disused Stations: Seacombe|work=Subterranea Britannica|accessdate=22 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Since closure==\nThe cutting in which the line was situated is now the approach road to the [[Kingsway Tunnel|Kingsway (Wallasey) Tunnel]].  Traces of the immediate approach to the station can be found at the rear of the [[supermarket]] car park in Church Road in the form of bridge stonework and a small section of sandstone wall at the roundabout facing the Seacombe Ferry Terminal.<ref name=DRS />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite journal |last=Aves |first=Bill |editor1-first=Martin |editor1-last=Smith |date=May 2011 |title=Unsung heroes - N4 and N5 0-6-2Ts (Part Two) |journal=Railway Bylines |volume=16| issue=6 |publisher=Irwell Press Limited |location= Radstock |issn=1360-2098|oclc=163283819 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book|title=Railway Stations of Wirral|author=Merseyside Railway History Group|pages=50\u201351|publisher=Ian & Marilyn Boumphrey|year=1994|isbn=1-899241-02-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=Wrexham to New Brighton|first1=Vic|last1=Mitchell|first2=Keith|last2=Smith|publisher=Middleton Press|location=West Sussex|year=2013|isbn=9781908174475|oclc=859543196|ref=harv}}\n\n{{Disused Rail Start}}\n{{Rail line |next=[[Liscard and Poulton railway station|Liscard and Poulton]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |route=[[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]]<br><small>[[Wirral Railway]]</small> |col={{WirralRly colour}} }}\n{{End box}}\n\n{{Closed stations Merseyside}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seacombe Railway Station}}\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in the Metropolitan Borough of Wirral]]\n[[Category:Former Wirral Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1895]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1960]]\n[[Category:Wallasey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Former railway station on the Wirral Railway in Wirral, England}}\n{{coord|53.4099|-3.0194|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=title}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n| name        = Seacombe\n| image       =[[File:Seacombe railway station 2042707 fbe01881.jpg|265px]]\n| caption     =The station in 1959\n| postgroup   = [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway|LMS]]\n| line        = [[Wirral Railway]]\n| locale      = [[Wallasey]]\n| borough     = [[Wirral Peninsula|Wirral]]\n| platforms   = 3\n| years       = 1 June 1895\n| events      = opened\n| years1      = 4 January 1960\n| events1     = passenger service withdrawn\n| years2      = 16 June 1963\n| events2     = closed completely\n| gridref     = SJ323908\n|}}\n<!-- start of article -->\n'''Seacombe railway station''' was located in [[Wallasey]], [[Wirral Peninsula|Wirral]], [[England]].<ref>[http://maps.nls.uk/geo/explore/#zoom=17&lat=53.4101&lon=-3.0197&layers=6&b=1 The station on a navigable Edwardian 6\" OS map with overlays, via ''National Library of Scotland'']</ref><ref>[http://www.RailMapOnline.com/UKIEMap.php?lat=53.40975&lng=-3.01865 The station on a navigable map with overlays, via ''Rail Map Online'']</ref> The station was opened by the [[Wirral Railway]] in 1895 and closed in 1963.\n\n==History==\nThe station was the terminus of a small branch line that ran from Seacombe Junction to opposite the ferry terminal at [[Seacombe]], adjacent to the [[River Mersey]].<ref name=MitchellXXXVI>{{harvnb|Mitchell|Smith|2013|loc=map XXXVI}}</ref> It was opened on 1 June 1895 as part of the [[Wirral Railway]], with only one other station ([[Liscard and Poulton railway station|Liscard and Poulton]]) on the stretch of line. The station's single platform was largely of timber construction with a small wooden waiting shelter near the exit. An additional platform was on the site,{{sfn|Aves|May 2011|p=330}} but was never used as the adjacent line was for the turning round of steam locomotives. The station buildings were constructed of [[corrugated iron]]. This was intended as a temporary measure, pending the building of a more permanent station adjoining the ferry terminal.<ref name=RSW>{{harvnb|Merseyside Railway History Group|1994|pages=50\u201351}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 1901 Seacombe became '''Seacombe & Egremont''', then reverted to its original name on 5 January 1953. The station saw regular passenger trips to [[Birkenhead]], [[New Brighton, Merseyside|New Brighton]] and [[Chester]] with occasional specials to [[Wrexham]] and [[West Kirby]]. However, the line was more focused on goods rather than passengers, so when the majority of the Wirral Railway was electrified in 1938 the Seacombe branch was omitted. Passenger services ended on 4 January 1960,<ref name=Mitchell108>{{harvnb|Mitchell|Smith|2013|loc=fig. 108}}</ref> although goods services continued for three further years until the station closed completely on 16 June 1963.<ref name=RSW /><ref name=DRS>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subbrit.org.uk/sb-sites/stations/s/seacombe/index.shtml|title=Disused Stations: Seacombe|work=Subterranea Britannica|accessdate=22 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Since closure==\nThe cutting in which the line was situated is now the approach road to the [[Kingsway Tunnel|Kingsway (Wallasey) Tunnel]].  Traces of the immediate approach to the station can be found at the rear of the [[supermarket]] car park in Church Road in the form of bridge stonework and a small section of sandstone wall at the roundabout facing the Seacombe Ferry Terminal.<ref name=DRS />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite journal |last=Aves |first=Bill |editor1-first=Martin |editor1-last=Smith |date=May 2011 |title=Unsung heroes - N4 and N5 0-6-2Ts (Part Two) |journal=Railway Bylines |volume=16| issue=6 |publisher=Irwell Press Limited |location= Radstock |issn=1360-2098|oclc=163283819 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book|title=Railway Stations of Wirral|author=Merseyside Railway History Group|pages=50\u201351|publisher=Ian & Marilyn Boumphrey|year=1994|isbn=1-899241-02-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=Wrexham to New Brighton|first1=Vic|last1=Mitchell|first2=Keith|last2=Smith|publisher=Middleton Press|location=West Sussex|year=2013|isbn=9781908174475|oclc=859543196|ref=harv}}\n\n{{Disused Rail Start}}\n{{Rail line |next=[[Liscard and Poulton railway station|Liscard and Poulton]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |route=[[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]]<br><small>[[Wirral Railway]]</small> |col={{WirralRly colour}} }}\n{{End box}}\n\n{{Closed stations Merseyside}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seacombe Railway Station}}\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in the Metropolitan Borough of Wirral]]\n[[Category:Former Wirral Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1895]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1960]]\n[[Category:Wallasey]]\n", "name_user": "Nempnet", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed citation anchor", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seacombe_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "1953 Coronation Honours", "text_new": "[[File:Elizabeth II & Philip after Coronation.JPG|thumb|Coronation portrait of Elizabeth II and Prince Philip]]\nThe '''1953 Coronation Honours''' were appointments by Queen [[Elizabeth II]] to [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the United Kingdom|various orders and honours]] on the occasion of [[Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II|her coronation]] on 2 June 1953. The honours were published in ''[[The London Gazette]]'' on 1 June 1953.<ref>{{London Gazette | issue=39863 |date=1 June 1953 |pages=2939\u20132993  |supp=y }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[The Times]]|publisher=The Times Digital Archive|date=1 June 1953|page=14|title=Queen's Coronation Honours}}</ref><ref>New Zealand list: {{London Gazette | issue=39866 |date=1 June 1953 |pages=3003\u20133006  |supp=y }}</ref>\n\nThe recipients of honours are displayed here as they were styled before their new honour. They are arranged by honour, with classes (Knight, Knight Grand Cross, ''etc.'') and then divisions (Military, Civil, ''etc.'') as appropriate.\n\n==United Kingdom==\n\n===Peerages===\n\n====[[Viscount]]s====\n*The Rt. Hon. [[Frederick Marquis, 1st Earl of Woolton|Frederick Marquis, Baron Woolton]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CH|DL}} Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster since 1952; Minister of Food, 1940\u20131943; Minister of Reconstruction and member of War Cabinet, 1943\u20131945; Lord President of the Council, 1945 and 1951\u20131952; ''by the name, title and style of '''Viscount Woolton''', of Liverpool in the County Palatine of Lancaster.''\n\n====[[Baron]]s====\n*Sir [[Peter Bennett, 1st Baron Bennett of Edgbaston|Peter Bennett]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|JP|MP}} Unionist Member of Parliament for Edgbaston since 1940. Parliamentary Secretary, Ministry of Labour and National Service, 1951\u20131952. For political and public services; ''by the name, style and title of '''Baron Bennett of Edgbaston''', of Sutton Coldfield in the County of Warwick.''\n*Sir [[Ralph Glyn, 1st Baron Glyn|Ralph Glyn]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|Bt|MC|DL|MP}} Unionist Member of Parliament for Abingdon since 1924 and for Clackmannan and East Stirlingshire, 1918\u20131922. Chairman, Select Committee of House of Commons on Estimates since 1951. For political and public services; ''by the name, style and title of '''Baron Glyn''', of Farnborough in the County of Berks.''\n*Sir [[Alfred Suenson-Taylor, 1st Baron Grantchester|Alfred Suenson-Taylor]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} President, London Liberal Party. For political and public services; ''by the name, style and title of '''Baron Grantchester''', of Knightsbridge in the City of Westminster.''\n\n===[[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellors]]===\nThe Queen appointed the following to Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council:\n*Sir [[Edward Bridges, 1st Baron Bridges|Edward Bridges]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|GCB|GCVO|MC}}\n*Sir [[Norman Brook, 1st Baron Normanbrook|Norman Brook]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|GCB}}\n*[[John Edwards (English politician)|John Edwards]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|MP}}\n*The Hon. [[Harold Holt]]\n*The Hon. [[John McEwen]]\n*Sir [[Patrick Spens, 1st Baron Spens|Patrick Spens]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KBE|QC|MP}}\n\n===[[Baronet]]cies===\n*[[Alfred Bossom]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|JP|MP}}\n*Sir [[Percy Mills, 1st Viscount Mills|Percy Mills]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KBE}}\n*Sir [[Price baronets|Henry Price]]\n*Major-General Sir [[Edward Spears]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KBE|CB|MC}}\n*Sir [[Sir Herbert Williams, 1st Baronet|Herbert Williams]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MP}}\n\n===[[Knights Bachelor]]===\n\n*[[Stephen Cecil Armitage]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}} Alderman, [[Nottingham City Council]]\n*[[John Heaton-Armstrong|John Dunamace Heaton-Armstrong]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MVO}} [[Chester Herald]]\n*[[Geoffrey Morris Barnett]], For political and public services in Leicester.\n*[[Dingwall Latham Bateson]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|MC}} President of the [[Law Society of England and Wales|Law Society]]\n*Alderman [[John William Bowen]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|JP}} Chairman of the North East Metropolitan [[Regional Hospital Board]], and the National Health Service General [[Whitley Council]]\n*[[John Bevan Braithwaite]], Chairman, Council of the [[London Stock Exchange|Stock Exchange]]\n*[[Edward Crisp Bullard]], Director, [[National Physical Laboratory (United Kingdom)|National Physical Laboratory]], Department of Scientific and Industrial Research\n*[[Sydney Camm]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}} Director and Chief Designer, [[Hawker Aircraft]], Ltd.\n*Professor [[David Campbell (pharmacologist)|David Campbell]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MC|MD}} President of the [[General Medical Council]]\n*[[George Norman Clark]], Provost of [[Oriel College, Oxford]]. For services to the study of history.\n*[[Bernard Henry Coode]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CB}} Clerk of Committees, House of Commons\n*[[Leonard Lumley Savage Dodsworth]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|JP}} For political and public services in York.\n*[[Patrick William Donner]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MP}} Conservative Member of Parliament for [[Basingstoke (UK Parliament constituency)|Basingstoke]] since 1935 and for [[Islington West (UK Parliament constituency)|West Islington]], 1931\u201335. For political and public services.\n*[[Walter James Drummond]], Deputy Chairman, [[National Coal Board]]\n*[[Edward Brown Ferguson]], Chairman, [[British Insurance Association]]\n*Major [[John Frederick Ferguson]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}} Chief Constable, [[Kent County Constabulary]]\n*[[Ernest Wensley Lapthorn Field]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}} Director, [[Scottish Engineering Employers' Association]]\n*[[Lionel Wray Fox]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CB|MC}} Chairman of the [[Prison Commission (England and Wales)|Prison Commission for England and Wales]]\n*[[John Gielgud|Arthur John Gielgud]], Actor\n*Colonel [[Louis Halle Gluckstein]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|QC|TD|DL}} Conservative Member of Parliament for [[Nottingham East (UK Parliament constituency)|East Nottingham]], 1931\u201345. For political and public services.\n*[[Stuart Goodwin|Stuart Coldwell Goodwin]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|JP}} For political and public services in Sheffield\n*[[David Edward Griffiths]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} Vice-Chairman of the Executive Committee, [[Royal Air Force Cinema Corporation]]\n*Alderman [[William Josiah Grimshaw]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|JP}} For political and public services in Middlesex\n*[[Kenneth George Grubb]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CMG}} President of the [[Church Missionary Society]]\n*[[John Berry Hobbs]], For services to cricket.\n*The Honourable [[Francis John Hopwood]], Managing Director, [[Shell Transport and Trading Company]], Ltd.\n*[[Harry Hyde (JP)|Harry Hyde]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|JP}} For political and public services in Lancashire.\n*[[Hugh Nicholas Linstead]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|MP}} Conservative Member of Parliament for [[Putney (UK Parliament constituency)|Putney]] since 1942. For political and public services.\n*[[George Donald Alastair MacDougall]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}} Chief Adviser, Statistical Branch, [[Paymaster General|Office of the Paymaster General]]\n*[[William McKie (musician)|William Neil McKie]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MVO}} Organist and Master of the Choristers, [[Westminster Abbey]]\n*Major [[Sydney Frank Markham]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MP}} Conservative Member of Parliament for [[Buckingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Buckingham]] since 1951; for [[Nottingham South (UK Parliament constituency)|South Nottingham]] (National), 1935\u20131945; and for [[Chatham (UK Parliament constituency)|Chatham]] (Labour), 1929\u201331. For political and public services.\n*Alderman [[James Marshall (alderman)|James Marshall]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|JP