ef>{{London Gazette | issue=39863 |date=1 June 1953 |pages=2939\u20132993  |supp=y }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[The Times]]|publisher=The Times Digital Archive|date=1 June 1953|page=14|title=Queen's Coronation Honours}}</ref><ref>New Zealand list: {{London Gazette | issue=39866 |date=1 June 1953 |pages=3003\u20133006  |supp=y }}</ref>\n\nThe recipients of honours are displayed here as they were styled before their new honour. They are arranged by honour, with classes (Knight, Knight Grand Cross, ''etc.'') and then divisions (Military, Civil, ''etc.'') as appropriate.\n\n==United Kingdom==\n\n===Peerages===\n\n====[[Viscount]]s====\n*The Rt. Hon. [[Frederick Marquis, 1st Earl of Woolton|Frederick Marquis, Baron Woolton]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CH|DL}} Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster since 1952; Minister of Food, 1940\u20131943; Minister of Reconstruction and member of War Cabinet, 1943\u20131945; Lord President of the Council, 1945 and 1951\u20131952; ''by the name, title and style of '''Viscount Woolton''', of Liverpool in the County Palatine of Lancaster.''\n\n====[[Baron]]s====\n*Sir [[Peter Bennett, 1st Baron Bennett of Edgbaston|Peter Bennett]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|JP|MP}} Unionist Member of Parliament for Edgbaston since 1940. Parliamentary Secretary, Ministry of Labour and National Service, 1951\u20131952. For political and public services; ''by the name, style and title of '''Baron Bennett of Edgbaston''', of Sutton Coldfield in the County of Warwick.''\n*Sir [[Ralph Glyn, 1st Baron Glyn|Ralph Glyn]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|Bt|MC|DL|MP}} Unionist Member of Parliament for Abingdon since 1924 and for Clackmannan and East Stirlingshire, 1918\u20131922. Chairman, Select Committee of House of Commons on Estimates since 1951. For political and public services; ''by the name, style and title of '''Baron Glyn''', of Farnborough in the County of Berks.''\n*Sir [[Alfred Suenson-Taylor, 1st Baron Grantchester|Alfred Suenson-Taylor]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} President, London Liberal Party. For political and public services; ''by the name, style and title of '''Baron Grantchester''', of Knightsbridge in the City of Westminster.''\n\n===[[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellors]]===\nThe Queen appointed the following to Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council:\n*Sir [[Edward Bridges, 1st Baron Bridges|Edward Bridges]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|GCB|GCVO|MC}}\n*Sir [[Norman Brook, 1st Baron Normanbrook|Norman Brook]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|GCB}}\n*[[John Edwards (English politician)|John Edwards]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|MP}}\n*The Hon. [[Harold Holt]]\n*The Hon. [[John McEwen]]\n*Sir [[Patrick Spens, 1st Baron Spens|Patrick Spens]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KBE|QC|MP}}\n\n===[[Baronet]]cies===\n*[[Alfred Bossom]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|JP|MP}}\n*Sir [[Percy Mills, 1st Viscount Mills|Percy Mills]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KBE}}\n*Sir [[Price baronets|Henry Price]]\n*Major-General Sir [[Edward Spears]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KBE|CB|MC}}\n*Sir [[Sir Herbert Williams, 1st Baronet|Herbert Williams]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MP}}\n\n===[[Knights Bachelor]]===\n\n*[[Stephen Cecil Armitage]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}} Alderman, [[Nottingham City Council]]\n*[[John Heaton-Armstrong|John Dunamace Heaton-Armstrong]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MVO}} [[Chester Herald]]\n*[[Geoffrey Morris Barnett]], For political and public services in Leicester.\n*[[Dingwall Latham Bateson]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|MC}} President of the [[Law Society of England and Wales|Law Society]]\n*Alderman [[John William Bowen]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|JP}} Chairman of the North East Metropolitan [[Regional Hospital Board]], and the National Health Service General [[Whitley Council]]\n*[[John Bevan Braithwaite]], Chairman, Council of the [[London Stock Exchange|Stock Exchange]]\n*[[Edward Crisp Bullard]], Director, [[National Physical Laboratory (United Kin